## Redis-Backed Throttler (Production)

Use Redis store for distributed rate limiting across multiple instances:

```ts
ThrottlerModule.forRootAsync({
  useFactory: () => ({
    throttlers: [{ ttl: 60000, limit: 60 }],
    storage: new ThrottlerStorageRedisService(redisClient),
  }),
}),
```

---

## Response on Rate Limit Exceeded

The global filter should handle `ThrottlerException`:

```json
{
  "success": false,
  "statusCode": 429,
  "message": "Too many requests. Please try again later."
}
```

Include `Retry-After` header:

```ts
// In GlobalExceptionFilter
if (exception instanceof ThrottlerException) {
  response.header('Retry-After', '60');
  // return 429 response
}
```

---

## Rules

- Apply rate limiting globally — never rely on individual routes to opt-in
- Auth endpoints must always have stricter limits than general API
- Use Redis store in production for distributed rate limiting
- Webhook endpoints skip throttle — they're server-to-server calls
- Internal service-to-service endpoints can use `@SkipThrottle()`
- Always return `Retry-After` header with 429 responses

---

## Forbidden

❌ No rate limiting on auth endpoints
❌ In-memory throttler in production (won't work across instances)
❌ Rate limiting only on frontend (backend must enforce)
❌ Missing 429 response on exceeded limits
❌ Same rate limit for public and admin endpoints
